# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: spectre-mitigation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] In computer architecture, a **branch predictor** is a digital circuit that tries to guess which way a branch (e.g., an if–then–else structure) will go before this is known definitively.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The purpose of the branch predictor is to improve the flow in the instruction pipeline.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Branch predictors play a critical role in achieving high performance in many modern pipelined microprocessor architectures.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Two-way branching is usually implemented with a conditional jump instruction.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] A conditional jump can either be "taken" and jump to a different place in program memory, or it can be "not taken" and continue execution immediately after the conditional jump.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] It is not known for certain whether a conditional jump will be taken or not taken until the condition has been calculated and the conditional jump has passed the execution stage in the instruction pipeline (see fig.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Without branch prediction, the processor would have to wait until the conditional jump instruction has passed the execute stage before the next instruction can enter the fetch stage in the pipeline.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The branch predictor attempts to avoid this waste of time by trying to guess whether the conditional jump is most likely to be taken or not taken.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The branch that is guessed to be the most likely is then fetched and speculatively executed.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] If it is later detected that the guess was wrong, then the speculatively executed or partially executed instructions are discarded and the pipeline starts over with the correct branch, incurring a delay.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The time that is wasted in case of a **branch misprediction** is equal to the number of stages in the pipeline from the fetch stage to the execute stage.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Modern microprocessors tend to have quite long pipelines so that the misprediction delay is between 10 and 20 clock cycles.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] As a result, making a pipeline longer increases the need for a more advanced branch predictor.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The first time a conditional jump instruction is encountered, there is not much information to base a prediction on.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] However, the branch predictor keeps records of whether or not branches are taken, so when it encounters a conditional jump that has been seen several times before, it can base the prediction on the recorded history.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The branch predictor may, for example, recognize that the conditional jump is taken more often than not, or that it is taken every second time.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Branch prediction is not the same as branch target prediction.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Branch prediction attempts to guess whether a conditional jump will be taken or not.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Branch target prediction attempts to guess the target of a taken conditional or unconditional jump before it is computed by decoding and executing the instruction itself.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Branch prediction and branch target prediction are often combined into the same circuitry.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Static prediction is the simplest branch prediction technique because it does not rely on information about the dynamic history of code executing.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Instead, it predicts the outcome of a branch based solely on the branch instruction.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Early implementations of SPARC and MIPS (two of the first commercial RISC architectures) used single-direction static branch prediction: they always predict that a conditional jump will not be taken, so they always fetch the next sequential instruction.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Only when the branch or jump is evaluated and found to be taken, does the instruction pointer get set to a non-sequential address.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Both CPUs fetch instructions in one cycle and evaluate branches in the decode stage.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] As a result, the branch target recurrence is two cycles long, and the machine always fetches the instruction immediately after any taken branch.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Both architectures define branch delay slots in order to utilize these fetched instructions.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] A more-advanced form of static prediction assumes that backward branches will be taken and forward branches will not.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] (A backward branch is one that has a target address that is lower than its own address.) This rule increases prediction accuracy in loops, which can be constructed with a backward branch at the end that is mostly taken, or a forward branch at the beginning that is mostly not taken.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] With processors that use this prediction method, ordering the instructions can maximize branch-prediction accuracy.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The RISC-V ISA recommends that software written for RISC-V harts (hardware threads), or generated to run on RISC-V harts, be optimized with the assumption that backward branches are taken and forward branches are not.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Some processors accept branch-prediction hints that override the static prediction.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The Intel Pentium 4 and Pentium 4E accept branch-prediction hints as prefixes.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] In the presence of dynamic prediction, static prediction offers almost no benefit, and overriding the static prediction helps even less.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Intel's subsequent Pentium M and Core2 processors ignore branch-prediction hint prefixes.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] No x86 manufacturer has re-introduced prediction hints.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Dynamic branch predictors naturally fall back on static branch prediction when they have no cached information (such as the first time a given branch is encountered).
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Both the Motorola MPC7450 (G4e) and the Intel Pentium 4 fall back on static prediction.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] In static prediction, all decisions are made at compile time, before the execution of the program.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Dynamic branch prediction uses information about taken or not-taken branches gathered at run-time to predict the outcome of a branch.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Random branch prediction means taking a random guess at whether a branch will be taken, each time it is executed.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The cost for a pseudorandom number generator is low compared to other techniques.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Random prediction guarantees a 50% correct prediction rate that cannot be increased or reduced by any means.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] (And it makes timing even more nondeterministic or unpredictable than other methods.) Static branch prediction (assuming forward branches are taken and backward branches are not) predicts each branch with an accuracy ranging from 0% to 100%, with the overall success rate somewhere in-between.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Unoptimized code is very likely to run with better than 50% prediction success; even 90% is likely.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] If the compiler does some instruction reordering, it makes the correct branch prediction rate higher than for unoptimized code.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Static branch prediction long ago surpassed random branch prediction.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Dynamic branch prediction has surpassed static branch prediction and is commonplace, despite the added complexity.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Some superscalar processors (MIPS R8000, Alpha 21264, and Alpha 21464 (EV8)) fetch each line of instructions with a pointer to the next line.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] This next-line predictor handles branch target prediction as well as branch direction prediction.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] When a next-line predictor points to aligned groups of 2, 4, or 8 instructions, the branch target will usually not be the first instruction fetched, and so the initial instructions fetched are wasted.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Assuming for simplicity, a uniform distribution of branch targets, 0.5, 1.5, and 3.5 instructions fetched are discarded, respectively.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Since the branch itself will generally not be the last instruction in an aligned group, instructions after the taken branch (or its delay slot) will be discarded.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Once again, assuming a uniform distribution of branch instruction placements, 0.5, 1.5, and 3.5 instructions fetched are discarded.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The discarded instructions at the branch and destination lines add up to nearly a complete fetch cycle, even for a single-cycle next-line predictor.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] A 1-bit saturating counter (essentially a flip-flop) records the last outcome of the branch.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] This is the most simple version of dynamic branch predictor possible, although it is not very accurate.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] When a branch is evaluated, the corresponding state machine is updated.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Branches evaluated as not taken change the state toward strongly not taken, and branches evaluated as taken change the state toward strongly taken.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The advantage of the two-bit counter scheme over a one-bit scheme is that a conditional jump has to deviate twice from what it has done most in the past before the prediction changes.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] For example, a loop-closing conditional jump is mispredicted once rather than twice.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The original, non-MMX Intel Pentium processor uses a saturating counter, though with an imperfect implementation.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] On the SPEC'89 benchmarks, very large bimodal predictors saturate at 93.5% correct, once every branch maps to a unique counter.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The predictor table is indexed with the instruction address bits, so that the processor can fetch a prediction for every instruction before the instruction is decoded.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The Two-Level Branch Predictor, also referred to as Correlation-Based Branch Predictor, uses a two-dimensional table of counters, also called "Pattern History Table".
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] If an `if` statement is executed three times, the decision made on the third execution might depend upon whether the previous two were taken or not.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] In such scenarios, a two-level adaptive predictor works more efficiently than a saturation counter.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Conditional jumps that are taken every second time or have some other regularly recurring pattern are not predicted well by the saturating counter.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] A two-level adaptive predictor remembers the history of the last n occurrences of the branch and uses one saturating counter for each of the possible 2n history patterns.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] This means that the last two occurrences of the branch are stored in a two-bit shift register.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] This branch history register can have four different binary values, 00, 01, 10, and 11, where zero means "not taken" and one means "taken".
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] A pattern history table contains four entries per branch, one for each of the 22 = 4 possible branch histories, and each entry in the table contains a two-bit saturating counter of the same type as in figure 2 for each branch.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The branch history register is used for choosing which of the four saturating counters to use.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] If the history is 00, then the first counter is used; if the history is 11, then the last of the four counters is used.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Assume, for example, that a conditional jump is taken every third time.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] In this case, entry number 00 in the pattern history table will go to state "strongly taken", indicating that after two zeroes comes a one.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Entry number 01 will go to state "strongly not taken", indicating that after 01 comes a zero.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The same is the case with entry number 10, while entry number 11 is never used because there are never two consecutive ones.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The general rule for a two-level adaptive predictor with an n-bit history is that it can predict any repetitive sequence with any period if all n-bit sub-sequences are different.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The advantage of the two-level adaptive predictor is that it can quickly learn to predict an arbitrary repetitive pattern.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Yeh and Yale Patt at the University of Michigan.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Since the initial publication in 1991, this method has become very popular, with it being used for later Pentium processors like the Pentium MMX.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Variants of this prediction method are used in most modern microprocessors.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] A two-level branch predictor where the second level is replaced with a neural network has been proposed.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] A local branch predictor has a separate history buffer for each conditional jump instruction.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] It may use a two-level adaptive predictor.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The history buffer is separate for each conditional jump instruction, while the pattern history table may be separate as well or it may be shared between all conditional jumps.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The Intel Pentium MMX, Pentium II, and Pentium III have local branch predictors with a local 4-bit history and a local pattern history table with 16 entries for each conditional jump.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] On the SPEC'89 benchmarks, very large local predictors saturate at 97.1% correct.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] A global branch predictor does not keep a separate history record for each conditional jump.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Instead it keeps a shared history of all conditional jumps.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The advantage of a shared history is that any correlation between different conditional jumps is part of making the predictions.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The disadvantage is that the history is diluted by irrelevant information if the different conditional jumps are uncorrelated, and that the history buffer may not include any bits from the same branch if there are many other branches in between.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] This scheme is better than the saturating counter scheme only for large table sizes, and it is rarely as good as local prediction.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The history buffer must be longer in order to make a good prediction.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The size of the pattern history table grows exponentially with the size of the history buffer.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Hence, the big pattern history table must be shared among all conditional jumps.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] A two-level adaptive predictor with globally shared history buffer and pattern history table is called a "gshare" predictor if it xors the global history and branch PC, and "gselect" if it concatenates them.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Global branch prediction is used in AMD processors, and in Intel Pentium M, Core, Core 2, and Silvermont-based Atom processors.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] An alloyed branch predictor combines the local and global prediction principles by concatenating local and global branch histories, possibly with some bits from the program counter as well.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Tests indicate that the VIA Nano processor may be using this technique.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] An agree predictor is a two-level adaptive predictor with globally shared history buffer and pattern history table, and an additional local saturating counter.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The outputs of the local and the global predictors are XORed with each other to give the final prediction.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The purpose is to reduce contentions in the pattern history table where two branches with opposite prediction happen to share the same entry in the pattern history table.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] A hybrid predictor, also called combined predictor, implements more than one prediction mechanism.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The final prediction is based either on a meta-predictor that remembers which of the predictors has made the best predictions in the past, or a majority vote function based on an odd number of different predictors.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Scott McFarling proposed combined branch prediction in his 1993 paper.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] On the SPEC'89 benchmarks, such a predictor is about as good as the local predictor.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Predictors like gshare use multiple table entries to track the behavior of any particular branch.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] This multiplication of entries makes it much more likely that two branches will map to the same table entry (a situation called aliasing), which in turn makes it much more likely that prediction accuracy will suffer for those branches.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Once you have multiple predictors, it is beneficial to arrange that each predictor will have different aliasing patterns, so that it is more likely that at least one predictor will have no aliasing.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Combined predictors with different indexing functions for the different predictors are called *gskew* predictors, and are analogous to skewed associative caches used for data and instruction caching.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] A conditional jump that controls a loop is best predicted with a special loop predictor.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] A conditional jump in the bottom of a loop that repeats N times will be taken N-1 times and then not taken once.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] If the conditional jump is placed at the top of the loop, it will be not taken N-1 times and then taken once.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] A conditional jump that goes many times one way and then the other way once is detected as having loop behavior.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Such a conditional jump can be predicted easily with a simple counter.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] A loop predictor is part of a hybrid predictor where a meta-predictor detects whether the conditional jump has loop behavior.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] An indirect jump instruction can choose among more than two branches.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Some processors have specialized indirect branch predictors.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Newer processors from Intel and AMD can predict indirect branches by using a two-level adaptive predictor.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] This kind of instruction contributes more than one bit to the history buffer.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The zEC12 and later z/Architecture processors from IBM support a BRANCH PREDICTION PRELOAD instruction that can preload the branch predictor entry for a given instruction with a branch target address constructed by adding the contents of a general-purpose register to an immediate displacement value.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Processors without this mechanism will simply predict an indirect jump to go to the same target as it did last time.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] A function will normally return to where it is called from.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The return instruction is an indirect jump that reads its target address from the call stack.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Many microprocessors have a separate prediction mechanism for return instructions.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] This mechanism is based on a so-called *return stack buffer*, which is a local mirror of the call stack.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The size of the return stack buffer is typically 4–16 entries.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The trade-off between fast branch prediction and good branch prediction is sometimes dealt with by having two branch predictors.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The first branch predictor is fast and simple.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The second branch predictor, which is slower, more complex, and with bigger tables, will override a possibly wrong prediction made by the first predictor.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The Alpha 21264 and Alpha EV8 microprocessors used a fast single-cycle next-line predictor to handle the branch target recurrence and provide a simple and fast branch prediction.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Because the next-line predictor is so inaccurate, and the branch resolution recurrence takes so long, both cores have two-cycle secondary branch predictors that can override the prediction of the next-line predictor at the cost of a single lost fetch cycle.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The Intel Core i7 has two branch target buffers and possibly two or more branch predictors.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Machine learning for branch prediction using LVQ and multilayer perceptrons, called "neural branch prediction", was proposed by Lucian Vintan (Lucian Blaga University of Sibiu).
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] One year later he developed the perceptron branch predictor.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The neural branch predictor research was developed much further by Daniel Jimenez.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] In 2001, the first perceptron predictor was presented that was feasible to implement in hardware.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The first commercial implementation of a perceptron branch predictor was in AMD's Piledriver microarchitecture.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The main advantage of the neural predictor is its ability to exploit long histories while requiring only linear resource growth.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Classical predictors require exponential resource growth.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Jimenez reports a global improvement of 5.7% over a McFarling-style hybrid predictor.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] He also used a gshare/perceptron overriding hybrid predictors.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The main disadvantage of the perceptron predictor is its high latency.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Even after taking advantage of high-speed arithmetic tricks, the computation latency is relatively high compared to the clock period of many modern microarchitectures.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] In order to reduce the prediction latency, Jimenez proposed in 2003 the *fast-path neural predictor*, where the perceptron predictor chooses its weights according to the current branch's path, rather than according to the branch's PC.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Many other researchers developed this concept (A.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Most of the state-of-the-art branch predictors are using a perceptron predictor (see Intel's "Championship Branch Prediction Competition").
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Intel already implements this idea in one of the IA-64's simulators (2003).
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The AMD Ryzen multi-core processor's Infinity Fabric and the Samsung Exynos processors include perceptron-based neural branch predictors.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The IBM 7030 Stretch, designed in the late 1950s, pre-executes all unconditional branches and any conditional branches that depended on the index registers.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] For other conditional branches, the first two production models implemented predict untaken; subsequent models were changed to implement predictions based on the current values of the indicator bits (corresponding to today's condition codes).
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The Stretch designers had considered static hint bits in the branch instructions early in the project but decided against them.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Misprediction recovery was provided by the lookahead unit on Stretch, and part of Stretch's reputation for less-than-stellar performance was blamed on the time required for misprediction recovery.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Subsequent IBM large computer designs did not use branch prediction with speculative execution until the IBM 3090 in 1985.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Two-bit predictors were introduced by Tom McWilliams and Curt Widdoes in 1977 for the Lawrence Livermore National Lab S-1 supercomputer and independently by Jim Smith in 1979 at CDC.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Microprogrammed processors, popular from the 1960s to the 1980s and beyond, took multiple cycles per instruction, and generally did not require branch prediction.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] However, in addition to the IBM 3090, there are several other examples of microprogrammed designs that incorporated branch prediction.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The Burroughs B4900, a microprogrammed COBOL machine released around 1982, was pipelined and used branch prediction.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The B4900 branch prediction history state is stored back into the in-memory instructions during program execution.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The B4900 implements 4-state branch prediction by using 4 semantically equivalent branch opcodes to represent each branch operator type.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The opcode used indicated the history of that particular branch instruction.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] If the hardware determines that the branch prediction state of a particular branch needs to be updated, it rewrites the opcode with the semantically equivalent opcode that hinted the proper history.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] US patent 4,435,756 and others were granted on this scheme.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The DEC VAX 9000, announced in 1989, is both microprogrammed and pipelined, and performs branch prediction.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The first commercial RISC processors, the MIPS R2000 and R3000 and the earlier SPARC processors, do only trivial "not-taken" branch prediction.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Because they use branch delay slots, fetched just one instruction per cycle, and execute in-order, there is no performance loss.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The later R4000 uses the same trivial "not-taken" branch prediction, and loses two cycles to each taken branch because the branch resolution recurrence is four cycles long.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Branch prediction became more important with the introduction of pipelined superscalar processors like the Intel Pentium, DEC Alpha 21064, the MIPS R8000, and the IBM POWER series.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] These processors all rely on one-bit or simple bimodal predictors.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The DEC Alpha 21264 (EV6) uses a next-line predictor overridden by a combined local predictor and global predictor, where the combining choice is made by a bimodal predictor.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The AMD K8 has a combined bimodal and global predictor, where the combining choice is another bimodal predictor.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] This processor caches the base and choice bimodal predictor counters in bits of the L2 cache otherwise used for ECC.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] As a result, it has effectively very large base and choice predictor tables, and parity rather than ECC on instructions in the L2 cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The parity design is sufficient, since any instruction suffering a parity error can be invalidated and refetched from memory.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The Alpha 21464 (EV8, cancelled late in design) had a minimum branch misprediction penalty of 14 cycles.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] It was to use a complex but fast next-line predictor overridden by a combined bimodal and majority-voting predictor.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The majority vote was between the bimodal and two gskew predictors.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] In 2018 a catastrophic security vulnerability called Spectre was made public by Google's Project Zero and other researchers.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] Affecting virtually all modern CPUs, the vulnerability involves priming the branch predictors so another process (or the kernel) will mispredict a branch and use secret data as an array index, evicting one of the attacker's cache lines.
[src:spectre-mitigation/branch-predictor] The attacker can time access to their own array to find out which one, turning this CPU internal (microarchitectural) state into a value the attacker can save which has information about values they could not read directly.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] A **CPU cache** is a hardware cache used by the central processing unit (CPU) of a computer to reduce the average cost (time or energy) to access data from the main memory.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] A cache is a smaller, faster memory, located closer to a processor core, which stores copies of the data from frequently used main memory locations, avoiding the need to always refer to main memory which may be tens to hundreds of times slower to access.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Cache memory is typically implemented with static random-access memory (SRAM), which requires multiple transistors to store a single bit.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] This makes it expensive in terms of the area it takes up, and in modern CPUs the cache is typically the largest part by chip area.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The size of the cache needs to be balanced with the general desire for smaller chips which cost less.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Some modern designs implement some or all of their cache using the physically smaller eDRAM, which is slower to use than SRAM but allows larger amounts of cache for any given amount of chip area.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Most CPUs have a hierarchy of multiple cache levels (L1, L2, often L3, and rarely even L4), with separate instruction-specific (I-cache) and data-specific (D-cache) caches at level 1.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The different levels are implemented in different areas of the chip; L1 is located as close to a CPU core as possible and thus offers the highest speed due to short signal paths, but requires careful design.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] L2 caches are physically separate from the CPU and operate slower, but place fewer demands on the chip designer and can be made much larger without impacting the CPU design.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] L3 caches are generally shared among multiple CPU cores.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Other types of caches exist (that are not counted towards the "cache size" of the most important caches mentioned above), such as the translation lookaside buffer (TLB) which is part of the memory management unit (MMU) which most CPUs have.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Input/output sections also often contain data buffers that serve a similar purpose.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] To access data in main memory, a multi-step process is used and each step introduces a delay.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] For instance, to read a value from memory in a simple computer system the CPU first selects the address to be accessed by expressing it on the address bus and waiting a fixed time to allow the value to settle.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The memory device with that value, normally implemented in DRAM, holds that value in a very low-energy form that is not powerful enough to be read directly by the CPU.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Instead, it has to copy that value from storage into a small buffer which is connected to the data bus.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] It then waits a certain time to allow this value to settle before reading the value from the data bus.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] By locating the memory physically closer to the CPU the time needed for the buses to settle is reduced, and by replacing the DRAM with SRAM, which hold the value in a form that does not require amplification to be read, the delay within the memory itself is eliminated.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] This makes the cache much faster both to respond and to read or write.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] SRAM, however, requires anywhere from four to six transistors to hold a single bit, depending on the type, whereas DRAM generally uses one transistor and one capacitor per bit, which makes it able to store much more data for any given chip area.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Implementing some memory in a faster format can lead to large performance improvements.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] When trying to read from or write to a location in the memory, the processor checks whether the data from that location is already in the cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] If so, the processor will read from or write to the cache instead of the much slower main memory.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Used to speed up virtual-to-physical address translation for both executable instructions and data.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] A single TLB can be provided for access to both instructions and data, or a separate Instruction TLB (ITLB) and data TLB (DTLB) can be provided.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] (MMU) and not directly related to the CPU caches.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Early examples of CPU caches include the Atlas 2 and the IBM System/360 Model 85 in the 1960s.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The first CPUs that used a cache had only one level of cache; unlike later level 1 cache, it was not split into L1d (for data) and L1i (for instructions).
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Split L1 cache started in 1976 with the IBM 801 CPU, became mainstream in the late 1980s, and in 1997 entered the embedded CPU market with the ARMv5TE.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] As of 2015, even sub-dollar SoCs split the L1 cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] They also have L2 caches and, for larger processors, L3 caches as well.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The L2 cache is usually not split, and acts as a common repository for the already split L1 cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Every core of a multi-core processor has a dedicated L1 cache and is usually not shared between the cores.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The L2 cache, and lower-level caches, may be shared between the cores.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] L4 cache is currently uncommon, and is generally dynamic random-access memory (DRAM) on a separate die or chip, rather than static random-access memory (SRAM).
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] An exception to this is when eDRAM is used for all levels of cache, down to L1.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Historically L1 was also on a separate die, however bigger die sizes have allowed integration of it as well as other cache levels, with the possible exception of the last level.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Each extra level of cache tends to be smaller and faster than the lower levels.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Caches (like for RAM historically) have generally been sized in powers of: 2, 4, 8, 16 etc.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] KiB; when up to MiB sizes (i.e. for larger non-L1), very early on the pattern broke down, to allow for larger caches without being forced into the doubling-in-size paradigm, with e.g.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Intel Core 2 Duo with 3 MiB L2 cache in April 2008.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] This happened much later for L1 caches, as their size is generally still a small number of KiB.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] In 2020, some Intel Atom CPUs (with up to 24 cores) have (multiple of) 4.5 MiB and 15 MiB cache sizes.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Data is transferred between memory and cache in blocks of fixed size, called *cache lines* or *cache blocks*.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] When a cache line is copied from memory into the cache, a cache entry is created.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The cache entry will include the copied data as well as the requested memory location (called a tag).
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] When the processor needs to read or write a location in memory, it first checks for a corresponding entry in the cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The cache checks for the contents of the requested memory location in any cache lines that might contain that address.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] If the processor finds that the memory location is in the cache, a **cache hit** has occurred.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] However, if the processor does not find the memory location in the cache, a **cache miss** has occurred.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] In the case of a cache hit, the processor immediately reads or writes the data in the cache line.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] For a cache miss, the cache allocates a new entry and copies data from main memory, then the request is fulfilled from the contents of the cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] To make room for the new entry on a cache miss, the cache may have to evict one of the existing entries.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The heuristic it uses to choose the entry to evict is called the replacement policy.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The fundamental problem with any replacement policy is that it must predict which existing cache entry is least likely to be used in the future.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Predicting the future is generally difficult, so there is no perfect method to choose among the variety of replacement policies available.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] One popular replacement policy, least-recently used (LRU), replaces the least recently accessed entry.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Marking some memory ranges as non-cacheable can improve performance, by avoiding caching of memory regions that are rarely re-accessed.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] This avoids the overhead of loading something into the cache without having any reuse.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Cache entries may also be disabled or locked depending on the context.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] If data are written to the cache, at some point they must also be written to main memory; the timing of this write is known as the write policy.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] In a write-through cache, every write to the cache causes a write to main memory.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Alternatively, in a write-back or copy-back cache, writes are not immediately mirrored to the main memory, with locations been written over being marked as dirty, being written back to the main memory only when they are evicted from the cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] For this reason, a read miss in a write-back cache may sometimes require two memory accesses to service: one to first write the dirty location to main memory, and then another to read the new location from memory.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Also, a write to a main memory location that is not yet mapped in a write-back cache may evict an already dirty location, thereby freeing that cache space for the new memory location.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] There are intermediate policies as well.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The cache may be write-through, but the writes may be held in a store data queue temporarily, usually so multiple stores can be processed together (which can reduce bus turnarounds and improve bus utilization).
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Cached data from the main memory may be changed by other entities (e.g., peripherals using direct memory access (DMA) or another core in a multi-core processor), in which case the copy in the cache may become out-of-date or stale.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Alternatively, when a CPU in a multiprocessor system updates data in the cache, copies of data in caches associated with other CPUs become stale.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Communication protocols between the cache managers that keep the data consistent are known as cache coherence protocols.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Cache performance measurement has become important in recent times where the speed gap between the memory performance and the processor performance is increasing exponentially.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The cache was introduced to reduce this speed gap.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Thus knowing how well the cache is able to bridge the gap in the speed of processor and memory becomes important, especially in high-performance systems.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The cache hit rate and the cache miss rate play an important role in determining this performance.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] To improve the cache performance, reducing the miss rate becomes one of the necessary steps among other steps.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Decreasing the access time to the cache also gives a boost to its performance and helps with optimization.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The time taken to fetch one cache line from memory (read latency due to a cache miss) matters because the CPU will run out of work while waiting for the cache line.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] When a CPU reaches this state, it is called a stall.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] As CPUs become faster compared to main memory, stalls due to cache misses displace more potential computation; modern CPUs can execute hundreds of instructions in the time taken to fetch a single cache line from main memory.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Various techniques have been employed to keep the CPU busy during this time, including out-of-order execution in which the CPU attempts to execute independent instructions after the instruction that is waiting for the cache miss data.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Another technology, used by many processors, is simultaneous multithreading (SMT), which allows an alternate thread to use the CPU core while the first thread waits for required CPU resources to become available.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The placement policy decides where in the cache a copy of a particular entry of main memory will go.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] If the placement policy is free to choose any entry in the cache to hold the copy, the cache is called *fully associative*.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] At the other extreme, if each entry in the main memory can go in just one place in the cache, the cache is *direct-mapped*.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Many caches implement a compromise in which each entry in the main memory can go to any one of N places in the cache, and are described as N-way set associative.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] For example, the level-1 data cache in an AMD Athlon is two-way set associative, which means that any particular location in main memory can be cached in either of two locations in the level-1 data cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Choosing the right value of associativity involves a trade-off.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] If there are ten places to which the placement policy could have mapped a memory location, then to check if that location is in the cache, ten cache entries must be searched.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Checking more places takes more power and chip area, and potentially more time.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] On the other hand, caches with more associativity suffer fewer misses (see conflict misses), so that the CPU wastes less time reading from the slow main memory.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The general guideline is that doubling the associativity, from direct mapped to two-way, or from two-way to four-way, has about the same effect on raising the hit rate as doubling the cache size.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] However, increasing associativity more than four does not improve hit rate as much, and are generally done for other reasons (see virtual aliasing).
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Some CPUs can dynamically reduce the associativity of their caches in low-power states, which acts as a power-saving measure.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] In this cache organization, each location in the main memory can go in only one entry in the cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Therefore, a direct-mapped cache can also be called a "one-way set associative" cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] It does not have a placement policy as such, since there is no choice of which cache entry's contents to evict.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] This means that if two locations map to the same entry, they may continually knock each other out.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Although simpler, a direct-mapped cache needs to be much larger than an associative one to give comparable performance, and it is more unpredictable.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Let x be block number in cache, y be block number of memory, and n be number of blocks in cache, then mapping is done with the help of the equation *x* = *y* mod *n*.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] One benefit of this scheme is that the tags stored in the cache do not have to include that part of the main memory address which is implied by the cache memory's index.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Since the cache tags have fewer bits, they require fewer transistors, take less space on the processor circuit board or on the microprocessor chip, and can be read and compared faster.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Also LRU algorithm is especially simple since only one bit needs to be stored for each pair.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] One of the advantages of a direct-mapped cache is that it allows simple and fast speculation.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Once the address has been computed, the one cache index which might have a copy of that location in memory is known.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] That cache entry can be read, and the processor can continue to work with that data before it finishes checking that the tag actually matches the requested address.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The idea of having the processor use the cached data before the tag match completes can be applied to associative caches as well.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] A subset of the tag, called a *hint*, can be used to pick just one of the possible cache entries mapping to the requested address.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The entry selected by the hint can then be used in parallel with checking the full tag.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The hint technique works best when used in the context of address translation, as explained below.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Other schemes have been suggested, such as the *skewed cache*, where the index for way 0 is direct, as above, but the index for way 1 is formed with a hash function.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] A good hash function has the property that addresses which conflict with the direct mapping tend not to conflict when mapped with the hash function, and so it is less likely that a program will suffer from an unexpectedly large number of conflict misses due to a pathological access pattern.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The downside is extra latency from computing the hash function.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Additionally, when it comes time to load a new line and evict an old line, it may be difficult to determine which existing line was least recently used, because the new line conflicts with data at different indexes in each way; LRU tracking for non-skewed caches is usually done on a per-set basis.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Nevertheless, skewed-associative caches have major advantages over conventional set-associative ones.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] A true set-associative cache tests all the possible ways simultaneously, using something like a content-addressable memory.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] A pseudo-associative cache tests each possible way one at a time.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] A hash-rehash cache and a column-associative cache are examples of a pseudo-associative cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] In the common case of finding a hit in the first way tested, a pseudo-associative cache is as fast as a direct-mapped cache, but it has a much lower conflict miss rate than a direct-mapped cache, closer to the miss rate of a fully associative cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Comparing with a direct-mapped cache, a set associative cache has a reduced number of bits for its cache set index that maps to a cache set, where multiple ways or blocks stays, such as 2 blocks for a 2-way set associative cache and 4 blocks for a 4-way set associative cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Comparing with a direct mapped cache, the unused cache index bits become a part of the tag bits.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] For example, a 2-way set associative cache contributes 1 bit to the tag and a 4-way set associative cache contributes 2 bits to the tag.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The basic idea of the multicolumn cache is to use the set index to map to a cache set as a conventional set associative cache does, and to use the added tag bits to index a way in the set.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] For example, in a 4-way set associative cache, the two bits are used to index way 00, way 01, way 10, and way 11, respectively.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] This double cache indexing is called a "major location mapping", and its latency is equivalent to a direct-mapped access.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Extensive experiments in multicolumn cache design shows that the hit ratio to major locations is as high as 90%.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] If cache mapping conflicts with a cache block in the major location, the existing cache block will be moved to another cache way in the same set, which is called "selected location".
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Because the newly indexed cache block is a most recently used (MRU) block, it is placed in the major location in multicolumn cache with a consideration of temporal locality.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Since multicolumn cache is designed for a cache with a high associativity, the number of ways in each set is high; thus, it is easy find a selected location in the set.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] A selected location index by an additional hardware is maintained for the major location in a cache block.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Multicolumn cache remains a high hit ratio due to its high associativity, and has a comparable low latency to a direct-mapped cache due to its high percentage of hits in major locations.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The *data block* (cache line) contains the actual data fetched from the main memory.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The *tag* contains (part of) the address of the actual data fetched from the main memory.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The "size" of the cache is the amount of main memory data it can hold.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] This size can be calculated as the number of bytes stored in each data block times the number of blocks stored in the cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] An effective memory address which goes along with the cache line (memory block) is split (MSB to LSB) into the tag, the index and the block offset.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The index describes which cache set that the data has been put in.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The index length is $\lceil \log _{2}(s)\rceil$ bits for s cache sets.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The block offset specifies the desired data within the stored data block within the cache row.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Typically the effective address is in bytes, so the block offset length is $\lceil \log _{2}(b)\rceil$ bits, where b is the number of bytes per data block.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The tag contains the most significant bits of the address, which are checked against all rows in the current set (the set has been retrieved by index) to see if this set contains the requested address.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Some authors refer to the block offset as simply the "offset" or the "displacement".
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The original Pentium 4 processor had a four-way set associative L1 data cache of 8 KiB in size, with 64-byte cache blocks.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Hence, there are 8 KiB / 64 = 128 cache blocks.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The number of sets is equal to the number of cache blocks divided by the number of ways of associativity, what leads to 128 / 4 = 32 sets, and hence 25 = 32 different indices.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Since the CPU address is 32 bits wide, this implies 32 − 5 − 6 = 21 bits for the tag field.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The original Pentium 4 processor also had an eight-way set associative L2 integrated cache 256 KiB in size, with 128-byte cache blocks.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] This implies 32 − 8 − 7 = 17 bits for the tag field.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] An instruction cache requires only one flag bit per cache row entry: a valid bit.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The valid bit indicates whether or not a cache block has been loaded with valid data.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] On power-up, the hardware sets all the valid bits in all the caches to "invalid".
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Some systems also set a valid bit to "invalid" at other times, such as when multi-master bus snooping hardware in the cache of one processor hears an address broadcast from some other processor, and realizes that certain data blocks in the local cache are now stale and should be marked invalid.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] A data cache typically requires two flag bits per cache line – a valid bit and a dirty bit.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Having a dirty bit set indicates that the associated cache line has been changed since it was read from main memory ("dirty"), meaning that the processor has written data to that line and the new value has not propagated all the way to main memory.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] A cache miss is a failed attempt to read or write a piece of data in the cache, which results in a main memory access with much longer latency.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] There are three kinds of cache misses: instruction read miss, data read miss, and data write miss.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Most general purpose CPUs implement some form of virtual memory.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] To summarize, either each program running on the machine sees its own simplified address space, which contains code and data for that program only, or all programs run in a common virtual address space.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] A program executes by calculating, comparing, reading and writing to addresses of its virtual address space, rather than addresses of physical address space, making programs simpler and thus easier to write.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Virtual memory requires the processor to translate virtual addresses generated by the program into physical addresses in main memory.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The portion of the processor that does this translation is known as the memory management unit (MMU).
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The fast path through the MMU can perform those translations stored in the translation lookaside buffer (TLB), which is a cache of mappings from the operating system's page table, segment table, or both.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] One early virtual memory system, the IBM M44/44X, required an access to a mapping table held in core memory before every programmed access to main memory.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] With no caches, and with the mapping table memory running at the same speed as main memory this effectively cut the speed of memory access in half.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Two early machines that used a page table in main memory for mapping, the IBM System/360 Model 67 and the GE 645, both had a small associative memory as a cache for accesses to the in-memory page table.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Both machines predated the first machine with a cache for main memory, the IBM System/360 Model 85, so the first hardware cache used in a computer system was not a data or instruction cache, but rather a TLB.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The speed of this recurrence (the *load latency*) is crucial to CPU performance, and so most modern level-1 caches are virtually indexed, which at least allows the MMU's TLB lookup to proceed in parallel with fetching the data from the cache RAM.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] But virtual indexing is not the best choice for all cache levels.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The cost of dealing with virtual aliases grows with cache size, and as a result most level-2 and larger caches are physically indexed.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Caches have historically used both virtual and physical addresses for the cache tags, although virtual tagging is now uncommon.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] If the TLB lookup can finish before the cache RAM lookup, then the physical address is available in time for tag compare, and there is no need for virtual tagging.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Large caches, then, tend to be physically tagged, and only small, very low latency caches are virtually tagged.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] In recent general-purpose CPUs, virtual tagging has been superseded by virtual hints, as described below.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] A cache that relies on virtual indexing and tagging becomes inconsistent after the same virtual address is mapped into different physical addresses (homonym), which can be solved by using physical address for tagging, or by storing the address space identifier in the cache line.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] However, the latter approach does not help against the synonym problem, in which several cache lines end up storing data for the same physical address.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Writing to such locations may update only one location in the cache, leaving the others with inconsistent data.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] This issue may be solved by using non-overlapping memory layouts for different address spaces, or otherwise the cache (or a part of it) must be flushed when the mapping changes.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The great advantage of virtual tags is that, for associative caches, they allow the tag match to proceed before the virtual to physical translation is done.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] However, coherence probes and evictions present a physical address for action.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The hardware must have some means of converting the physical addresses into a cache index, generally by storing physical tags as well as virtual tags.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] For comparison, a physically tagged cache does not need to keep virtual tags, which is simpler.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] When a virtual to physical mapping is deleted from the TLB, cache entries with those virtual addresses will have to be flushed somehow.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Alternatively, if cache entries are allowed on pages not mapped by the TLB, then those entries will have to be flushed when the access rights on those pages are changed in the page table.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] It is also possible for the operating system to ensure that no virtual aliases are simultaneously resident in the cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The operating system makes this guarantee by enforcing page coloring, which is described below.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Some early RISC processors (SPARC, RS/6000) took this approach.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] It has not been used recently, as the hardware cost of detecting and evicting virtual aliases has fallen and the software complexity and performance penalty of perfect page coloring has risen.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] It can be useful to distinguish the two functions of tags in an associative cache: they are used to determine which way of the entry set to select, and they are used to determine if the cache hit or missed.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The second function must always be correct, but it is permissible for the first function to guess, and get the wrong answer occasionally.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Some processors (e.g. early SPARCs) have caches with both virtual and physical tags.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The virtual tags are used for way selection, and the physical tags are used for determining hit or miss.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] This kind of cache enjoys the latency advantage of a virtually tagged cache, and the simple software interface of a physically tagged cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] It bears the added cost of duplicated tags, however.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Also, during miss processing, the alternate ways of the cache line indexed have to be probed for virtual aliases and any matches evicted.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The extra area (and some latency) can be mitigated by keeping *virtual hints* with each cache entry instead of virtual tags.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] These hints are a subset or hash of the virtual tag, and are used for selecting the way of the cache from which to get data and a physical tag.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Like a virtually tagged cache, there may be a virtual hint match but physical tag mismatch, in which case the cache entry with the matching hint must be evicted so that cache accesses after the cache fill at this address will have just one hint match.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Since virtual hints have fewer bits than virtual tags distinguishing them from one another, a virtually hinted cache suffers more conflict misses than a virtually tagged cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Perhaps the ultimate reduction of virtual hints can be found in the Pentium 4 (Willamette and Northwood cores).
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] In these processors the virtual hint is effectively two bits, and the cache is four-way set associative.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Effectively, the hardware maintains a simple permutation from virtual address to cache index, so that no content-addressable memory (CAM) is necessary to select the right one of the four ways fetched.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Large physically indexed caches (usually secondary caches) run into a problem: the operating system rather than the application controls which pages collide with one another in the cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Differences in page allocation from one program run to the next lead to differences in the cache collision patterns, which can lead to very large differences in program performance.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] These differences can make it very difficult to get a consistent and repeatable timing for a benchmark run.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] To understand the problem, consider a CPU with a 1 MiB physically indexed direct-mapped level-2 cache and 4 KiB virtual memory pages.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Sequential physical pages map to sequential locations in the cache until after 256 pages the pattern wraps around.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] We can label each physical page with a color of 0–255 to denote where in the cache it can go.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Locations within physical pages with different colors cannot conflict in the cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Programmers attempting to make maximum use of the cache may arrange their programs' access patterns so that only 1 MiB of data need be cached at any given time, thus avoiding capacity misses.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] But they should also ensure that the access patterns do not have conflict misses.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] One way to think about this problem is to divide up the virtual pages the program uses and assign them virtual colors in the same way as physical colors were assigned to physical pages before.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Programmers can then arrange the access patterns of their code so that no two pages with the same virtual color are in use at the same time.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] There is a wide literature on such optimizations (e.g. loop nest optimization), largely coming from the High Performance Computing (HPC) community.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The snag is that while all the pages in use at any given moment may have different virtual colors, some may have the same physical colors.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] In fact, if the operating system assigns physical pages to virtual pages randomly and uniformly, it is extremely likely that some pages will have the same physical color, and then locations from those pages will collide in the cache (this is the birthday paradox).
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The solution is to have the operating system attempt to assign different physical color pages to different virtual colors, a technique called *page coloring*.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Although the actual mapping from virtual to physical color is irrelevant to system performance, odd mappings are difficult to keep track of and have little benefit, so most approaches to page coloring simply try to keep physical and virtual page colors the same.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] If the operating system can guarantee that each physical page maps to only one virtual color, then there are no virtual aliases, and the processor can use virtually indexed caches with no need for extra virtual alias probes during miss handling.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] Alternatively, the OS can flush a page from the cache whenever it changes from one virtual color to another.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] As mentioned above, this approach was used for some early SPARC and RS/6000 designs.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] The software page coloring technique has been used to effectively partition the shared Last level Cache (LLC) in multicore processors.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p01] This operating system-based LLC management in multicore processors has been adopted by Intel.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Modern processors have multiple interacting on-chip caches.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The operation of a particular cache can be completely specified by the cache size, the cache block size, the number of blocks in a set, the cache set replacement policy, and the cache write policy (write-through or write-back).
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] While all of the cache blocks in a particular cache are the same size and have the same associativity, typically the "higher-level" caches (called Level 1 cache) have a smaller number of blocks, smaller block size, and fewer blocks in a set, but have very short access times.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Level 2 and below) have progressively larger numbers of blocks, larger block size, more blocks in a set, and relatively longer access times, but are still much faster than main memory.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Cache entry replacement policy is determined by a cache algorithm selected to be implemented by the processor designers.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] In some cases, multiple algorithms are provided for different kinds of work loads.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Pipelined CPUs access memory from multiple points in the pipeline: instruction fetch, virtual-to-physical address translation, and data fetch (see classic RISC pipeline).
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The natural design is to use different physical caches for each of these points, so that no one physical resource has to be scheduled to service two points in the pipeline.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Thus the pipeline naturally ends up with at least three separate caches (instruction, TLB, and data), each specialized to its particular role.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] A **victim cache** is a cache used to hold blocks evicted from a CPU cache upon replacement.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The victim cache lies between the main cache and its refill path, and holds only those blocks of data that were evicted from the main cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The victim cache is usually fully associative, and is intended to reduce the number of conflict misses.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Many commonly used programs do not require an associative mapping for all the accesses.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] In fact, only a small fraction of the memory accesses of the program require high associativity.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The victim cache exploits this property by providing high associativity to only these accesses.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] It was introduced by Norman Jouppi from DEC in 1990.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Intel's *Crystalwell* variant of its Haswell processors introduced an on-package 128 MiB eDRAM Level 4 cache which serves as a victim cache to the processors' Level 3 cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] In the Skylake microarchitecture the Level 4 cache no longer works as a victim cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] One of the more extreme examples of cache specialization is the **trace cache** (also known as *execution trace cache*) found in the Intel Pentium 4 microprocessors.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] A trace cache is a mechanism for increasing the instruction fetch bandwidth and decreasing power consumption (in the case of the Pentium 4) by storing traces of instructions that have already been fetched and decoded.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] A trace cache stores instructions either after they have been decoded, or as they are retired.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Generally, instructions are added to trace caches in groups representing either individual basic blocks or dynamic instruction traces.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The Pentium 4's trace cache stores micro-operations resulting from decoding x86 instructions, providing also the functionality of a micro-operation cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Having this, the next time an instruction is needed, it does not have to be decoded into micro-ops again.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Write Coalescing Cache is a special cache that is part of L2 cache in AMD's Bulldozer microarchitecture.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Stores from both L1D caches in the module go through the WCC, where they are buffered and coalesced.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The WCC's task is reducing number of writes to the L2 cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] A **micro-operation cache** (**μop cache**, **uop cache** or **UC**) is a specialized cache that stores micro-operations of decoded instructions, as received directly from the instruction decoders or from the instruction cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] When an instruction needs to be decoded, the μop cache is checked for its decoded form which is re-used if cached; if it is not available, the instruction is decoded and then cached.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] One of the early works describing μop cache as an alternative frontend for the Intel P6 processor family is the 2001 paper *"Micro-Operation Cache: A Power Aware Frontend for Variable Instruction Length ISA"*.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Later, Intel included μop caches in its Sandy Bridge processors and in successive microarchitectures like Ivy Bridge and Haswell.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] AMD implemented a μop cache in their Zen microarchitecture.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Fetching complete pre-decoded instructions eliminates the need to repeatedly decode variable length complex instructions into simpler fixed-length micro-operations, and simplifies the process of predicting, fetching, rotating and aligning fetched instructions.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] A μop cache effectively offloads the fetch and decode hardware, thus decreasing power consumption and improving the frontend supply of decoded micro-operations.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The μop cache also increases performance by more consistently delivering decoded micro-operations to the backend and eliminating various bottlenecks in the CPU's fetch and decode logic.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] A μop cache has many similarities with a trace cache, although a μop cache is much simpler thus providing better power efficiency; this makes it better suited for implementations on battery-powered devices.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The main disadvantage of the trace cache, leading to its power inefficiency, is the hardware complexity required for its heuristic deciding on caching and reusing dynamically created instruction traces.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] A **branch target cache** or **branch target instruction cache**, the name used on ARM microprocessors, is a specialized cache which holds the first few instructions at the destination of a taken branch.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] This is used by low-powered processors which do not need a normal instruction cache because the memory system is capable of delivering instructions fast enough to satisfy the CPU without one.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] However, this only applies to consecutive instructions in sequence; it still takes several cycles of latency to restart instruction fetch at a new address, causing a few cycles of pipeline bubble after a control transfer.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] A branch target cache provides instructions for those few cycles avoiding a delay after most taken branches.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] This allows full-speed operation with a much smaller cache than a traditional full-time instruction cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Smart Cache shares the actual cache memory between the cores of a multi-core processor.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] In comparison to a dedicated per-core cache, the overall cache miss rate decreases when cores do not require equal parts of the cache space.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Consequently, a single core can use the full level 2 or level 3 cache while the other cores are inactive.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Furthermore, the shared cache makes it faster to share memory among different execution cores.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Another issue is the fundamental tradeoff between cache latency and hit rate.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Larger caches have better hit rates but longer latency.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] To address this tradeoff, many computers use multiple levels of cache, with small fast caches backed up by larger, slower caches.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Multi-level caches generally operate by checking the fastest but smallest cache, *level 1* (**L1**), first; if it hits, the processor proceeds at high speed.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] If that cache misses, the slower but larger next level cache, *level 2* (**L2**), is checked, and so on, before accessing external memory.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] As the latency difference between main memory and the fastest cache has become larger, some processors have begun to utilize as many as three levels of on-chip cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Price-sensitive designs used this to pull the entire cache hierarchy on-chip, but by the 2010s some of the highest-performance designs returned to having large off-chip caches, which is often implemented in eDRAM and mounted on a multi-chip module, as a fourth cache level.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] In rare cases, such as in the mainframe CPU IBM z15 (2019), all levels down to L1 are implemented by eDRAM, replacing SRAM entirely (for cache, SRAM is still used for registers).
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Apple's ARM-based Apple silicon series, starting with the A14 and M1, have a 192 KiB L1i cache for each of the high-performance cores, an unusually large amount; however the high-efficiency cores only have 128 KiB.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Since then other processors such as Intel's Lunar Lake and Qualcomm's Oryon have also implemented similar L1i cache sizes.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The benefits of L3 and L4 caches depend on the application's access patterns.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] However, with register renaming most compiler register assignments are reallocated dynamically by hardware at runtime into a register bank, allowing the CPU to break false data dependencies and thus easing pipeline hazards.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Register files sometimes also have hierarchy: The Cray-1 (circa 1976) had eight address "A" and eight scalar data "S" registers that were generally usable.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] There was also a set of 64 address "B" and 64 scalar data "T" registers that took longer to access, but were faster than main memory.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The "B" and "T" registers were provided because the Cray-1 did not have a data cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] When considering a chip with multiple cores, there is a question of whether the caches should be shared or local to each core.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Implementing shared cache inevitably introduces more wiring and complexity.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] But then, having one cache per *chip*, rather than *core*, greatly reduces the amount of space needed, and thus one can include a larger cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Typically, sharing the L1 cache is undesirable because the resulting increase in latency would make each core run considerably slower than a single-core chip.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] For example, an eight-core chip with three levels may include an L1 cache for each core, one intermediate L2 cache for each pair of cores, and one L3 cache shared between all cores.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] A shared highest-level cache (usually L3, called before accessing memory), is usually referred to as a *last-level cache* (LLC).
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Additional techniques are used for increasing the level of parallelism when LLC is shared between multiple cores, including slicing it into multiple pieces which are addressing certain ranges of memory addresses, and can be accessed independently.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] In a separate cache structure, instructions and data are cached separately, meaning that a cache line is used to cache either instructions or data, but not both; various benefits have been demonstrated with separate data and instruction translation lookaside buffers.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] In a unified structure, this constraint is not present, and cache lines can be used to cache both instructions and data.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Multi-level caches introduce new design decisions.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] For instance, in some processors, all data in the L1 cache must also be somewhere in the L2 cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] These caches are called *strictly inclusive*.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Other processors (like the AMD Athlon) have *exclusive* caches: data are guaranteed to be in at most one of the L1 and L2 caches, never in both.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Still other processors (like the Intel Pentium II, III, and 4) do not require that data in the L1 cache also reside in the L2 cache, although it may often do so.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] There is no universally accepted name for this intermediate policy; two common names are "non-exclusive" and "partially-inclusive".
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The advantage of exclusive caches is that they store more data.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] This advantage is larger when the exclusive L1 cache is comparable to the L2 cache, and diminishes if the L2 cache is many times larger than the L1 cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] When the L1 misses and the L2 hits on an access, the hitting cache line in the L2 is exchanged with a line in the L1.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] This exchange is quite a bit more work than just copying a line from L2 to L1, which is what an inclusive cache does.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] One advantage of strictly inclusive caches is that when external devices or other processors in a multiprocessor system wish to remove a cache line from the processor, they need only have the processor check the L2 cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] In cache hierarchies which do not enforce inclusion, the L1 cache must be checked as well.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] As a drawback, there is a correlation between the associativities of L1 and L2 caches: if the L2 cache does not have at least as many ways as all L1 caches together, the effective associativity of the L1 caches is restricted.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Another disadvantage of inclusive cache is that whenever there is an eviction in L2 cache, the (possibly) corresponding lines in L1 also have to get evicted in order to maintain inclusiveness.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] This is quite a bit of work, and would result in a higher L1 miss rate.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Another advantage of inclusive caches is that the larger cache can use larger cache lines, which reduces the size of the secondary cache tags.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Scratchpad memory (SPM), also known as scratchpad, scratchpad RAM or local store in computer terminology, is a high-speed internal memory used for temporary storage of calculations, data, and other work in progress.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] To illustrate both specialization and multi-level caching, here is the cache hierarchy of the K8 core in the AMD Athlon 64 CPU.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The K8 has four specialized caches: an instruction cache, an instruction TLB, a data TLB, and a data cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] There are second-level instruction and data TLBs, which store only PTEs mapping 4 KiB.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Both instruction and data caches, and the various TLBs, can fill from the large **unified** L2 cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] This cache is exclusive to both the L1 instruction and data caches, which means that any 8-byte line can only be in one of the L1 instruction cache, the L1 data cache, or the L2 cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] It is, however, possible for a line in the data cache to have a PTE which is also in one of the TLBs—the operating system is responsible for keeping the TLBs coherent by flushing portions of them when the page tables in memory are updated.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The K8 also caches information that is never stored in memory—prediction information.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] These caches are not shown in the above diagram.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] As is usual for this class of CPU, the K8 has fairly complex branch prediction, with tables that help predict whether branches are taken and other tables which predict the targets of branches and jumps.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Some of this information is associated with instructions, in both the level 1 instruction cache and the unified secondary cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The K8 uses an interesting trick to store prediction information with instructions in the secondary cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Lines in the secondary cache are protected from accidental data corruption (e.g. by an alpha particle strike) by either ECC or parity, depending on whether those lines were evicted from the data or instruction primary caches.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Since the parity code takes fewer bits than the ECC code, lines from the instruction cache have a few spare bits.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] These bits are used to cache branch prediction information associated with those instructions.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The net result is that the branch predictor has a larger effective history table, and so has better accuracy.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Other processors have other kinds of predictors (e.g., the store-to-load bypass predictor in the DEC Alpha 21264).
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] These predictors are caches in that they store information that is costly to compute.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Some of the terminology used when discussing predictors is the same as that for caches (one speaks of a **hit** in a branch predictor), but predictors are not generally thought of as part of the cache hierarchy.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The K8 keeps the instruction and data caches **coherent** in hardware, which means that a store into an instruction closely following the store instruction will change that following instruction.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Other processors, like those in the Alpha and MIPS family, have relied on software to keep the instruction cache coherent.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Stores are not guaranteed to show up in the instruction stream until a program calls an operating system facility to ensure coherency.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] In computer engineering, a *tag RAM* is used to specify which of the possible memory locations is currently stored in a CPU cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] For a simple, direct-mapped design fast SRAM can be used.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Higher associative caches usually employ content-addressable memory.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Cache **reads** are the most common CPU operation that takes more than a single cycle.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Program execution time tends to be very sensitive to the latency of a level-1 data cache hit.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] A great deal of design effort, and often power and silicon area are expended making the caches as fast as possible.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The simplest cache is a virtually indexed direct-mapped cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The virtual address is calculated with an adder, the relevant portion of the address extracted and used to index an SRAM, which returns the loaded data.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The data are byte aligned in a byte shifter, and from there are bypassed to the next operation.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] There is no need for any tag checking in the inner loop – in fact, the tags need not even be read.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Later in the pipeline, but before the load instruction is retired, the tag for the loaded data must be read, and checked against the virtual address to make sure there was a cache hit.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] On a miss, the cache is updated with the requested cache line and the pipeline is restarted.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] An associative cache is more complicated, because some form of tag must be read to determine which entry of the cache to select.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] An N-way set-associative level-1 cache usually reads all N possible tags and N data in parallel, and then chooses the data associated with the matching tag.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Level-2 caches sometimes save power by reading the tags first, so that only one data element is read from the data SRAM.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The adjacent diagram is intended to clarify the manner in which the various fields of the address are used.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Address bit 31 is most significant, bit 0 is least significant.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The diagram shows the SRAMs, indexing, and multiplexing for a 4 KiB, 2-way set-associative, virtually indexed and virtually tagged cache with 64 byte (B) lines, a 32-bit read width and 32-bit virtual address.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Because the cache is 4 KiB and has 64 B lines, there are just 64 lines in the cache, and we read two at a time from a Tag SRAM which has 32 rows, each with a pair of 21 bit tags.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Although any function of virtual address bits 31 through 6 could be used to index the tag and data SRAMs, it is simplest to use the least significant bits.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Similarly, because the cache is 4 KiB and has a 4 B read path, and reads two ways for each access, the Data SRAM is 512 rows by 8 bytes wide.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] A more modern cache might be 16 KiB, 4-way set-associative, virtually indexed, virtually hinted, and physically tagged, with 32 B lines, 32-bit read width and 36-bit physical addresses.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The read path recurrence for such a cache looks very similar to the path above.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Instead of tags, virtual hints are read, and matched against a subset of the virtual address.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Later on in the pipeline, the virtual address is translated into a physical address by the TLB, and the physical tag is read (just one, as the virtual hint supplies which way of the cache to read).
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Finally the physical address is compared to the physical tag to determine if a hit has occurred.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Some SPARC designs have improved the speed of their L1 caches by a few gate delays by collapsing the virtual address adder into the SRAM decoders.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The early history of cache technology is closely tied to the invention and use of virtual memory.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Because of scarcity and cost of semi-conductor memories, early mainframe computers in the 1960s used a complex hierarchy of physical memory, mapped onto a flat virtual memory space used by programs.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The memory technologies would span semi-conductor, magnetic core, drum and disc.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Virtual memory seen and used by programs would be flat and caching would be used to fetch data and instructions into the fastest memory ahead of processor access.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Extensive studies were done to optimize the cache sizes.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Optimal values were found to depend greatly on the programming language used with Algol needing the smallest and Fortran and Cobol needing the largest cache sizes.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] In the early days of microcomputer technology, memory access was only slightly slower than register access.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] But since the 1980s the performance gap between processor and memory has been growing.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Microprocessors have advanced much faster than memory, especially in terms of their operating frequency, so memory became a performance bottleneck.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] While it was technically possible to have all the main memory as fast as the CPU, a more economically viable path has been taken: use plenty of low-speed memory, but also introduce a small high-speed cache memory to alleviate the performance gap.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] This provided an order of magnitude more capacity—for the same price—with only a slightly reduced combined performance.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The first documented uses of a TLB were on the GE 645 and the IBM 360/67, both of which used an associative memory as a TLB.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The first documented use of an instruction cache was on the CDC 6600.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The first documented use of a data cache was on the IBM System/360 Model 85.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The 68010, released in 1982, has a "loop mode" which can be considered a tiny and special-case instruction cache that accelerates loops that consist of only two instructions.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The 68020, released in 1984, replaced that with a typical instruction cache of 256 bytes, being the first 68k series processor to feature true on-chip cache memory.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The 68030, released in 1987, is basically a 68020 core with an additional 256-byte data cache, an on-chip memory management unit (MMU), a process shrink, and added burst mode for the caches.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The 68040, released in 1990, has split instruction and data caches of four kilobytes each.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The 68060, released in 1994, has the following: 8 KiB data cache (four-way associative), 8 KiB instruction cache (four-way associative), 96-byte FIFO instruction buffer, 256-entry branch cache, and 64-entry address translation cache MMU buffer (four-way associative).
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] As the x86 microprocessors reached clock rates of 20 MHz and above in the 386, small amounts of fast cache memory began to be featured in systems to improve performance.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] This was because the DRAM used for main memory had significant latency, up to 120 ns, as well as refresh cycles.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The cache was constructed from more expensive, but significantly faster, SRAM memory cells, which at the time had latencies around 10–25 ns.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The early caches were external to the processor and typically located on the motherboard in the form of eight or nine DIP devices placed in sockets to enable the cache as an optional extra or upgrade feature.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Some versions of the Intel 386 processor could support 16 to 256 KiB of external cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] With the 486 processor, an 8 KiB cache was integrated directly into the CPU die.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] This cache was termed Level 1 or L1 cache to differentiate it from the slower on-motherboard, or Level 2 (L2) cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] These on-motherboard caches were much larger, with the most common size being 256 KiB.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] There were some system boards that contained sockets for the Intel 485Turbocache daughtercard which had either 64 or 128 Kbyte of cache memory.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The popularity of on-motherboard cache continued through the Pentium MMX era but was made obsolete by the introduction of SDRAM and the growing disparity between bus clock rates and CPU clock rates, which caused on-motherboard cache to be only slightly faster than main memory.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The next development in cache implementation in the x86 microprocessors began with the Pentium Pro, which brought the secondary cache onto the same package as the microprocessor, clocked at the same frequency as the microprocessor.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] On-motherboard caches enjoyed prolonged popularity thanks to the AMD K6-2 and AMD K6-III processors that still used Socket 7, which was previously used by Intel with on-motherboard caches.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] K6-III included 256 KiB on-die L2 cache and took advantage of the on-board cache as a third level cache, named L3 (motherboards with up to 2 MiB of on-board cache were produced).
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] After the Socket 7 became obsolete, on-motherboard cache disappeared from the x86 systems.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The three-level caches were used again first with the introduction of the Intel Xeon MP "Foster Core", where the L3 cache was added to the CPU die.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] It became common for the total cache sizes to be increasingly larger in newer processor generations, and recently (as of 2011) it is not uncommon to find Level 3 cache sizes of tens of megabytes.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Intel introduced a Level 4 on-package cache with the Haswell microarchitecture.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] *Crystalwell* Haswell CPUs, equipped with the GT3e variant of Intel's integrated Iris Pro graphics, effectively feature 128 MiB of embedded DRAM (eDRAM) on the same package.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] This L4 cache is shared dynamically between the on-die GPU and CPU, and serves as a victim cache to the CPU's L3 cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The Apple M1 CPU has 128 or 192 KiB of L1 instruction cache for each core (important for latency/single-thread performance), depending on core type.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] This is an unusually large L1 cache for any CPU type (not just for a laptop); the total cache memory size is not unusually large (the total is more important for throughput) for a laptop, and much larger total (e.g.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] L3 or L4) sizes are available in IBM's mainframes.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Early cache designs focused entirely on the direct cost of cache and RAM and average execution speed.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] More recent cache designs also consider energy efficiency, fault tolerance, and other goals.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] There are several tools available to computer architects to help explore tradeoffs between the cache cycle time, energy, and area; the CACTI cache simulator and the SimpleScalar instruction set simulator are two open-source options.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] A multi-ported cache is a cache which can serve more than one request at a time.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] When accessing a traditional cache we normally use a single memory address, whereas in a multi-ported cache we may request N addresses at a time – where N is the number of ports that connected through the processor and the cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] The benefit of this is that a pipelined processor may access memory from different phases in its pipeline.
[src:spectre-mitigation/cpu-cache-p02] Another benefit is that it allows the concept of super-scalar processors through different cache levels.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] In addition to vulnerabilities associated with installed applications, JIT engines used for JavaScript were found to be vulnerable.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] A website can read data stored in the browser for another website, or the browser's memory itself.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Two Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures records related to Spectre, CVE-2017-5753 (bounds check bypass, Spectre-V1, Spectre 1.0) and CVE-2017-5715 (branch target injection, Spectre-V2), have been issued.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] In early 2018, Intel reported that it would redesign its CPUs to help protect against the Spectre and related Meltdown vulnerabilities (specifically, Spectre variant 2 and Meltdown, but not Spectre variant 1).
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] On 8 October 2018, Intel was reported to have added hardware and firmware mitigations regarding Spectre and Meltdown vulnerabilities to its latest processors.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] For devices that were already vulnerable, software patches were released that addressed the issue at the cost of performance.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Mitigations were applied to the Linux kernel, the Windows operating system, and some vulnerable user-mode applications.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Yukiyasu Tsunoo and colleagues from NEC showed how to attack MISTY and DES symmetric key ciphers in 2002 and 2003, respectively.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] In 2005, Daniel Bernstein from the University of Illinois, Chicago, reported an extraction of an OpenSSL AES key via a cache timing attack, and Colin Percival had a working attack on the OpenSSL RSA key using the Intel processor's cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] In 2013, Yuval Yarom and Katrina Falkner from the University of Adelaide showed how measuring the access time to data lets a nefarious application determine if the information was read from the cache or not.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] If it were read from the cache, the access time would be very short, meaning the data read could contain the private key of encryption algorithms.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] This technique was used to successfully attack GnuPG, AES, and other cryptographic implementations.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] In January 2017, Anders Fogh gave a presentation at the Ruhr University Bochum about automatically finding covert channels, especially on processors with a pipeline used by more than one processor core.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Spectre proper was discovered independently by Jann Horn from Google's Project Zero and Paul Kocher in collaboration with Daniel Genkin, Mike Hamburg, Moritz Lipp, and Yuval Yarom.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] It was made public in conjunction with another vulnerability, Meltdown, on 3 January 2018, after the affected hardware vendors had already been made aware of the issue on 1 June 2017.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] The vulnerability was called Spectre because it was "based on the root cause, speculative execution.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] On 28 January 2018, it was reported that Intel shared news of the Meltdown and Spectre security vulnerabilities with Chinese technology companies before notifying the U.S. government of the flaws.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] On 29 January 2018, Microsoft was reported to have released a Windows update that disabled the problematic Intel Microcode fix—which had, in some cases, caused reboots, system instability, and data loss or corruption—issued earlier by Intel for the Spectre Variant 2 attack.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Woody Leonhard of *ComputerWorld* expressed a concern about installing the new Microsoft patch.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Since the disclosure of Spectre and Meltdown in January 2018, much research has been done on vulnerabilities related to speculative execution.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] On 3 May 2018, eight additional Spectre-class flaws provisionally named *Spectre-NG* by *c't* (a German computer magazine) were reported affecting Intel and possibly AMD and ARM processors.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Intel reported that they were preparing new patches to mitigate these flaws.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Affected are all Core i Series processors and Xeon derivatives since Nehalem (2010) and Atom-based processors since 2013.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Intel postponed their release of microcode updates to 10 July 2018.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] On 21 May 2018, Intel published information on the first two Spectre-NG class side-channel vulnerabilities: CVE-2018-3640 (Rogue System Register Read, Variant 3a) and CVE-2018-3639 (Speculative Store Bypass, Variant 4), also referred to as Intel SA-00115 and HP PSR-2018-0074, respectively.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] According to Amazon Germany, Cyberus Technology, SYSGO, and Colin Percival (FreeBSD), Intel revealed details on the third Spectre-NG variant CVE-2018-3665 (Lazy FP State Restore, Intel SA-00145) on 13 June 2018.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] It is also known as Lazy FPU state leak (abbreviated "LazyFP") and "Spectre-NG 3".
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] On 10 July 2018, Intel revealed details on another Spectre-NG class vulnerability called "Bounds Check Bypass Store" (BCBS), or "Spectre 1.1" (CVE-2018-3693), which was able to write as well as read out of bounds.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Another variant named "Spectre 1.2" was mentioned as well.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] In late July 2018, researchers at the universities of Saarland and California revealed *ret spec* (aka "Spectre v5") and *SpectreRSB*, new types of code execution vulnerabilities using the return stack buffer (RSB).
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] At the end of July 2018, researchers at the Graz University of Technology revealed "NetSpectre", a new type of remote attack similar to Spectre v1, but which does not need attacker-controlled code to be run on the target device.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] In November 2018, five new variants of the attacks were revealed.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Researchers attempted to compromise CPU protection mechanisms using code to exploit the CPU pattern history table, branch target buffer, return stack buffer, and branch history table.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] In August 2019, a related speculative execution CPU vulnerability, Spectre SWAPGS (CVE-2019-1125), was reported.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] In July 2020 a team of researchers from TU Kaiserslautern in Germany published a new Spectre variant called "Spectre-STC" (single-threaded contention).
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] This variant makes use of port contention in shared resources and can be applied even in single-threaded cores.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] In late April 2021, a related vulnerability was discovered that breaks through the security systems designed to mitigate Spectre through use of the micro-op cache.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] The vulnerability is known to affect Skylake and later processors from Intel and Zen-based processors from AMD.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] In February 2023, a team of researchers at North Carolina State University uncovered a new code execution vulnerability called "Spectre-HD", also known as "Spectre SRV" or "Spectre v6".
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] This vulnerability leverages speculative vectorization with the selective replay (SRV) technique showing "Leakage from Higher Dimensional Speculation".
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Instead of a single easy-to-fix vulnerability, the Spectre white paper describes a whole class of potential vulnerabilities.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] They are all based on exploiting side effects of speculative execution, a common means of hiding memory latency and so speeding up execution in modern microprocessors.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] In particular, Spectre centers on branch prediction, which is a special case of speculative execution.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Unlike the related Meltdown vulnerability disclosed at the same time, Spectre does not rely on a specific feature of a single processor's memory management and protection system, but is instead a more generalized idea.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] The starting point of the white paper is that of a side-channel timing attack applied to the branch prediction machinery of modern microprocessors with speculative execution.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] At the architectural level documented in processor data books, any results of misprediction are specified to be discarded.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] However, the speculative execution may still leave side effects, such as loaded cache lines.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] These can then affect the so-called non-functional aspects of the computing environment later on.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] If such side effects, including but not limited to memory access timing, are visible to a malicious program and can be engineered to depend on sensitive data held by the victim process, then these side effects can result in such data becoming discernible.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] This can happen despite the formal architecture-level security arrangements working as designed; in this case, lower, microarchitecture-level optimizations to code execution can leak information not essential to the correctness of normal program execution.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] It then goes on to show that the subsequent differences between cache hits and misses can be reliably timed, such that what should have been a simple non-functional timing difference can in fact be subverted into a covert channel that extracts information from an unrelated process's inner workings.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Finally, the paper concludes by generalizing the attack to any non-functional state of the victim process.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] It briefly discusses highly non-obvious, non-functional effects such as bus arbitration latency.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Spectre Variant 1, also called **Bounds Check Bypass**, is an exploit of CPU speculative execution in conditional branches related to memory access bounds.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] This occurs because the CPU speculatively accesses memory with specific bounds, such as arrays, leading to a bounds bypass (out-of-bounds index access).
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] This speculative execution happens before the CPU validates the bounds check or reverts after a misprediction occurs, resulting in a side-channel leakage.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] This attack is the result of conditional branch misprediction, which causes a vulnerable processor to speculatively access out-of-bounds data before the access is validated and before any exception arises.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Spectre Variant 2, also called **Branch Target Injection** (BTI), is an exploitation of the CPU's speculative execution of indirect branches, unlike Spectre Variant 1, which is related to conditional branches.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] This vulnerability arises due to misprediction by the indirect branch predictor.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] This vulnerability differs from Variant 1 because indirect branches are branches whose targets are unknown at compile time and need to be resolved dynamically.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] An attacker can poison the branch target buffer, causing the indirect branch predictor to mispredict and redirect execution to locations that the program's control flow would never legitimately reach.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] While Spectre is simpler to exploit with a compiled language such as C or C++ by locally executing machine code, it can also be remotely exploited by code hosted on remote malicious web pages, for example, interpreted languages like JavaScript, which run locally using a web browser.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] The scripted malware would then have access to all the memory mapped to the address space of the running browser.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] The exploit using remote JavaScript follows a similar flow to that of a local machine code exploit: flush cache → mistrain branch predictor → timed reads (tracking hits and misses).
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] The `clflush` instruction (cache-line flush) cannot be used directly from JavaScript, so flushing the cache requires another approach.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] There are several automatic cache eviction policies that the CPU may choose, and the attack relies on being able to force that eviction for the exploit to work.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] It was found that using a second index on the large array, which was kept several iterations behind the first index, would cause the least recently used (LRU) policy to be invoked.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] This allows the exploit to effectively clear the cache just by doing incremental reads on a large dataset.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Careful coding and analysis of the machine code executed by the just-in-time compilation (JIT) compiler was required to ensure the cache-clearing and exploitive reads were not optimized out.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] The branch predictor would then be mistrained by iterating over a very large dataset using bitwise operations for setting the index to in-range values, and then using an out-of-bounds address for the final iteration.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] A high-precision timer would then be required in order to determine if a set of reads led to a cache hit or a cache miss.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] While browsers like Chrome, Firefox have restrictions on the resolution of timers, the Spectre author was able to create a high-precision timer using the web worker feature of HTML5.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] As of 2018, almost every computer system is affected by Spectre, including desktops, laptops, and mobile devices.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Specifically, Spectre has been shown to work on Intel, AMD, ARM-based, and IBM processors.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Intel responded to the reported security vulnerabilities with an official statement.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] AMD originally acknowledged vulnerability to one of the Spectre variants (GPZ variant 1), but stated that vulnerability to another (GPZ variant 2) had not been demonstrated on AMD processors, claiming it posed a "near zero risk of exploitation" due to differences in AMD architecture.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] In an update nine days later, AMD said that "GPZ Variant 2 ... is applicable to AMD processors" and defined upcoming steps to mitigate the threat.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Several sources took AMD's news of the vulnerability to GPZ variant 2 as a change from AMD's prior claim, though AMD maintained that its position had not changed.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Researchers have indicated that the Spectre vulnerability can possibly affect some Intel, AMD, and ARM processors.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Specifically, processors with speculative execution are affected by these vulnerabilities.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] ARM has reported that the majority of their processors are not vulnerable, and published a list of the specific processors that are affected by the Spectre vulnerability: Cortex-R7, Cortex-R8, Cortex-A8, Cortex-A9, Cortex-A15, Cortex-A17, Cortex-A57, Cortex-A72, Cortex-A73 and ARM Cortex-A75 cores.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Other manufacturers' custom CPU cores implementing the ARM instruction set, such as those found in newer members of the Apple A series processors, have also been reported to be vulnerable.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] In general, higher-performance CPUs tend to have intensive speculative execution, making them vulnerable to Spectre.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Spectre has the potential of having a greater impact on cloud providers than Meltdown.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Whereas Meltdown allows unauthorized applications to read from privileged memory to obtain sensitive data from processes running on the same cloud server, Spectre can allow malicious programs to induce a hypervisor to transmit the data to a guest system running on top of it.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Since Spectre represents a whole class of attacks, a single patch is unlikely to address all vulnerabilities.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Several procedures to help protect home computers and related devices from the vulnerability have been published.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Spectre patches have been reported to significantly reduce performance, especially on older computers; on the eighth-generation Core platforms, benchmark performance drops of 2–14 percent have been measured.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] In early January 2018, Chris Hoffman of the website HowToGeek suggested that the fix would require "a complete hardware redesign for CPUs across the board" and noted how, once software fixes were released, slowdowns on patched computers were expected.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] As early as 2018, machine learning has been employed to detect attacks in real time.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] This has led to an arms race where attackers also employ machine learning to thwart machine learning-based detectors, and detectors in turn employ Generative Adversarial Networks to adapt detection techniques.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] On 4 January 2018, Google detailed a new technique on their security blog called "Retpoline" (a portmanteau of return and trampoline) which can overcome the Spectre vulnerability with a negligible amount of processor overhead.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] It involves compiler-level steering of indirect branches towards a different target that does not result in a vulnerable speculative out-of-order execution taking place.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] While it was developed for the x86 instruction set, Google engineers believe the technique is transferable to other processors as well.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] On 25 January 2018, the current status and possible future considerations in solving the Meltdown and Spectre vulnerabilities were presented.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] In March 2018, Intel announced that it had developed hardware fixes for Meltdown and Spectre-V2 only, but not Spectre-V1.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] The vulnerabilities were mitigated by a new partitioning system that improves process and privilege-level separation.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] On 8 October 2018, Intel is reported to have added hardware and firmware mitigations regarding Spectre and Meltdown vulnerabilities to its Coffee Lake-R processors and onwards.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] On 18 October 2018, MIT researchers suggested a new mitigation approach, called DAWG (Dynamically Allocated Way Guard), which may promise better security without compromising performance.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] On 26 November 2021, researchers from Texas A&M University and Intel showed that Spectre attacks (and other families of transient attacks) cannot be detected by typical antivirus or anti-malware software before they leak data.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] They show that it is easy to engineer evasive versions of these attacks to build malware.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] On 20 October 2022, researchers from North Carolina State University, UC San Diego and Intel announced that they were able to design the first machine learning detection technology that can detect transient attacks before leakage in the microarchitecture layer.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] This technology is also equipped with adversarial training, making it immune to a large category of adversarial and evasive versions of the Spectre attack.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] When Intel announced that Spectre mitigation can be switched on as a "security feature" instead of being an always-on bugfix, Linux creator Linus Torvalds called the patches "complete and utter garbage".
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Ingo Molnár then suggested the use of function tracing machinery in the Linux kernel to fix Spectre without Indirect Branch Restricted Speculation (IBRS) microcode support.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] This would, as a result, only have a performance impact on processors based on Intel Skylake and newer architectures.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] This ftrace and retpoline-based machinery was incorporated into Linux 4.15 and released in January 2018.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] On 2 March 2019, Microsoft released Windows 10 software mitigation to the Spectre v2 CPU vulnerability.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Initial mitigation efforts were not entirely without incident.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] At first, Spectre patches were reported to significantly slow down performance, especially on older computers.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] On the eighth generation Core platforms, benchmark performance drops of 2–14 percent were measured.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] On 18 January 2018, unwanted reboots were reported even for newer Intel chips.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Since exploitation of Spectre through JavaScript embedded in websites is possible, it was planned to include mitigations against the attack by default in Chrome 64.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] Chrome 63 users could manually mitigate the attack by enabling the site isolation feature (`chrome://flags#enable-site-per-process`).
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] As of Firefox 57.0.4, Mozilla was reducing the resolution of JavaScript timers to help prevent timing attacks, with additional work on time-fuzzing techniques planned for future releases.
[src:spectre-mitigation/retpoline] On January 15, 2018, Microsoft introduced mitigation for Spectre in Visual Studio.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] In computer security, a **side-channel attack** is a type of security exploit that uses information inadvertently leaked by a system—such as timing, power consumption, or electromagnetic or acoustic emissions—to gain unauthorized access to sensitive information.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] These attacks differ from those targeting flaws in the design of cryptographic protocols or algorithms (notwithstanding the fact that cryptanalysis may identify vulnerabilities relevant to both types of attacks).
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] Some side-channel attacks require technical knowledge of the internal operation of the system, others such as differential power analysis are effective as black-box attacks.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] Attempts to break a cryptosystem by deceiving or coercing people with legitimate access are not typically considered side-channel attacks: see social engineering and rubber-hose cryptanalysis.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] In all cases, the underlying principle is that physical effects caused by the operation of a cryptosystem (*on the side*) can provide useful extra information about secrets in the system, for example, the cryptographic key, partial state information, full or partial plaintexts and so forth.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] The term cryptophthora (secret degradation) is sometimes used to express the degradation of secret key material resulting from side-channel leakage.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] A **cache side-channel attack** works by monitoring security critical operations such as AES T-table entry or modular exponentiation or multiplication or memory accesses.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] The attacker then is able to recover the secret key depending on the accesses made (or not made) by the victim, deducing the encryption key.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] Also, unlike some of the other side-channel attacks, this method does not create a fault in the ongoing cryptographic operation and is invisible to the victim.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] In 2017, two CPU vulnerabilities (dubbed Meltdown and Spectre) were discovered, which can use a cache-based side channel to allow an attacker to leak memory contents of other processes and the operating system itself.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] A *power analysis* attack can provide even more detailed information by observing the power consumption of a hardware device such as CPU or cryptographic circuit.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] These attacks are roughly categorized into simple power analysis (SPA) and differential power analysis (DPA).
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] One example is Collide+Power, which affects nearly all CPUs.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] Other examples use machine learning approaches.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] Fluctuations in current also generate radio waves, enabling attacks that analyze measurements of electromagnetic (EM) emanations.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] These attacks typically involve similar statistical techniques as power-analysis attacks.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] A *deep-learning-based side-channel attack*, using the power and EM information across multiple devices has been demonstrated with the potential to break the secret key of a different but identical device in as low as a single trace.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] Historical analogues to modern side-channel attacks are known.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] A recently declassified NSA document reveals that as far back as 1943, an engineer with Bell telephone observed decipherable spikes on an oscilloscope associated with the decrypted output of a certain encrypting teletype.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] According to former MI5 officer Peter Wright, the British Security Service analyzed emissions from French cipher equipment in the 1960s.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] In the 1980s, Soviet eavesdroppers were suspected of having planted bugs inside IBM Selectric typewriters to monitor the electrical noise generated as the type ball rotated and pitched to strike the paper; the characteristics of those signals could determine which key was pressed.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] Power consumption of devices causes heating, which is offset by cooling effects.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] Temperature changes create thermally induced mechanical stress.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] This stress can create low level acoustic emissions from operating CPUs (about 10 kHz in some cases).
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] Recent research by Shamir et al. has suggested that information about the operation of cryptosystems and algorithms can be obtained in this way as well.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] This is an *acoustic cryptanalysis attack*.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] If the surface of the CPU chip, or in some cases the CPU package, can be observed, infrared images can also provide information about the code being executed on the CPU, known as a *thermal-imaging attack*.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] An *optical side-channel attack* examples include gleaning information from the hard disk activity indicator to reading a small number of photons emitted by transistors as they change state.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] Under the first category, displays with special shielding to lessen electromagnetic emissions, reducing susceptibility to TEMPEST attacks, are now commercially available.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] Power line conditioning and filtering can help deter power-monitoring attacks, although such measures must be used cautiously, since even very small correlations can remain and compromise security.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] Physical enclosures can reduce the risk of surreptitious installation of microphones (to counter acoustic attacks) and other micro-monitoring devices (against CPU power-draw or thermal-imaging attacks).
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] Another countermeasure (still in the first category) is to jam the emitted channel with noise.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] For instance, a random delay can be added to deter timing attacks, although adversaries can compensate for these delays by averaging multiple measurements (or, more generally, using more measurements in the analysis).
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] When the amount of noise in the side channel increases, the adversary needs to collect more measurements.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] Another countermeasure under the first category is to use security analysis software to identify certain classes of side-channel attacks that can be found during the design stages of the underlying hardware itself.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] Timing attacks and cache attacks are both identifiable through certain commercially available security analysis software platforms, which allow for testing to identify the attack vulnerability itself, as well as the effectiveness of the architectural change to circumvent the vulnerability.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] The most comprehensive method to employ this countermeasure is to create a Secure Development Lifecycle for hardware, which includes utilizing all available security analysis platforms at their respective stages of the hardware development lifecycle.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] In the case of timing attacks against targets whose computation times are quantized into discrete clock cycle counts, an effective countermeasure against is to design the software to be isochronous, that is to run in an exactly constant amount of time, independently of secret values.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] Such countermeasures can be difficult to implement in practice, since even individual instructions can have variable timing on some CPUs.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] One partial countermeasure against simple power attacks, but not differential power-analysis attacks, is to design the software so that it is "PC-secure" in the "program counter security model".
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] In a PC-secure program, the execution path does not depend on secret values.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] In other words, all conditional branches depend only on public information.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] On architectures where the instruction execution time is not data-dependent, a PC-secure program is also immune to timing attacks.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] Another way in which code can be non-isochronous is that modern CPUs have a memory cache: accessing infrequently used information incurs a large timing penalty, revealing some information about the frequency of use of memory blocks.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] Cryptographic code designed to resist cache attacks attempts to use memory in only a predictable fashion (like accessing only the input, outputs and program data, and doing so according to a fixed pattern).
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] For example, data-dependent table lookups must be avoided because the cache could reveal which part of the lookup table was accessed.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] Other partial countermeasures attempt to reduce the amount of information leaked from data-dependent power differences.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] Some operations use power that is correlated to the number of 1 bits in a secret value.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] Using a constant-weight code (such as using Fredkin gates or dual-rail encoding) can reduce the leakage of information about the Hamming weight of the secret value, although exploitable correlations are likely to remain unless the balancing is perfect.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] This "balanced design" can be approximated in software by manipulating both the data and its complement together.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] Several "secure CPUs" have been built as asynchronous CPUs; they have no global timing reference.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] While these CPUs were intended to make timing and power attacks more difficult, subsequent research found that timing variations in asynchronous circuits are harder to remove.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] Recently, white-box modeling was utilized to develop a low-overhead generic circuit-level countermeasure against both EM as well as power side-channel attacks.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] To minimize the effects of the higher-level metal layers in an IC acting as more efficient antennas, the idea is to embed the crypto core with a signature suppression circuit, routed locally within the lower-level metal layers, leading towards both power and EM side-channel attack immunity.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] As a countermeasure for message encryption, **masking** (also known as **blinding**) is effective against all side-channel attacks.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] The principle of masking is to avoid manipulating any sensitive value y directly, but rather manipulate a sharing of it: a set of variables (called "shares") $y_{1},...,y_{d}$ such that $y=y_{1}\oplus ...\oplus y_{d}$ (where $\oplus$ is the XOR operation).
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] An attacker must recover all the values of the shares to get any meaningful information.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] Since the decrypting system chose r , it can compute its inverse modulo m to cancel out the factor r in the result and obtain $y^{d}$ , the actual result of the decryption.
[src:spectre-mitigation/side-channel-attack] For attacks that require collecting side-channel information from operations with data *controlled by the attacker*, blinding is an effective countermeasure, since the actual operation is executed on a randomized version of the data, over which the attacker has no control or even knowledge.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] Modern computers are highly parallel devices, composed of components with very different performance characteristics.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] The prediction may be based on recent behavior of the system.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] When the earlier, slower operation completes, the microprocessor determines whether the prediction was correct or incorrect.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] If it was correct then execution proceeds uninterrupted; if it was incorrect then the microprocessor rolls back the speculatively executed operations and repeats the original instruction with the real result of the slow operation.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] Specifically, a *transient instruction* refers to an instruction processed by error by the processor (incriminating the branch predictor in the case of Spectre) which can affect the micro-architectural state of the processor, leaving the architectural state without any trace of its execution.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] In terms of the directly visible behavior of the computer it is as if the speculatively executed code "never happened".
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] However, this speculative execution may affect the state of certain components of the microprocessor, such as the cache, and this effect may be discovered by careful monitoring of the timing of subsequent operations.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] In early January 2018, it was reported that all Intel processors made since 1995 (besides Intel Itanium and pre-2013 Intel Atom) have been subject to two security flaws dubbed **Meltdown** and **Spectre**.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] The impact on performance resulting from software patches is "workload-dependent".
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] Several procedures to help protect home computers and related devices from the Spectre and Meltdown security vulnerabilities have been published.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] Spectre patches have been reported to significantly slow down performance, especially on older computers; on the newer 8th-generation Core platforms, benchmark performance drops of 2–14% have been measured.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] Meltdown patches may also produce performance loss.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] It is believed that "hundreds of millions" of systems could be affected by these flaws.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] More security flaws were disclosed on May 3, 2018, on August 14, 2018, on January 18, 2019, and on March 5, 2020.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] At the time, Intel was not commenting on this issue.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] On March 15, 2018, Intel reported that it will redesign its CPUs (performance losses to be determined) to protect against the Spectre security vulnerability, and expects to release the newly redesigned processors later in 2018.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] On May 3, 2018, eight additional Spectre-class flaws were reported.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] Intel reported that they are preparing new patches to mitigate these flaws.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] On August 14, 2018, Intel disclosed three additional chip flaws referred to as **L1 Terminal Fault (L1TF)**.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] They reported that previously released microcode updates, along with new, pre-release microcode updates can be used to mitigate these flaws.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] Coffee Lake-series CPUs are even more vulnerable, due to hardware mitigations for Spectre.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] On March 5, 2020, computer security experts reported another Intel chip security flaw, besides the Meltdown and Spectre flaws, with the systematic name CVE-2019-0090 (or "**Intel CSME Bug**").
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] This newly found flaw is not fixable with a firmware update, and affects nearly "all Intel chips released in the past five years".
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] In March 2021 AMD security researchers discovered that the Predictive Store Forwarding algorithm in Zen 3 CPUs could be used by malicious applications to access data it shouldn't be accessing.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] According to Phoronix there's little performance impact in disabling the feature.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] In June 2021, two new vulnerabilities, **Speculative Code Store Bypass** (**SCSB**, CVE-2021-0086) and **Floating Point Value Injection** (FPVI, CVE-2021-0089), affecting *all* modern x86-64 CPUs both from Intel and AMD were discovered.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] In order to mitigate them software has to be rewritten and recompiled.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] ARM CPUs are not affected by SCSB but some certain ARM architectures are affected by FPVI.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] Also in June 2021, MIT researchers revealed the **PACMAN** attack on Pointer Authentication Codes (PAC) in ARM v8.3A.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] In August 2021 a vulnerability called "**Transient Execution of Non-canonical Accesses**" affecting certain AMD CPUs was disclosed.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] It requires the same mitigations as the MDS vulnerability affecting certain Intel CPUs.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] Since most x86 software is already patched against MDS and this vulnerability has the exact same mitigations, software vendors don't have to address this vulnerability.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] In October 2021 for the first time ever a vulnerability similar to Meltdown was disclosed to be affecting all AMD CPUs however the company doesn't think any new mitigations have to be applied and the existing ones are already sufficient.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] In March 2022, a new variant of the Spectre vulnerability called **Branch History Injection** was disclosed.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] It affects certain ARM64 CPUs and the following Intel CPU families: Cascade Lake, Ice Lake, Tiger Lake and Alder Lake.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] According to Linux kernel developers AMD CPUs are also affected.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] In March 2022, a vulnerability affecting a wide range of AMD CPUs was disclosed under CVE-2021-26341.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] In June 2022, multiple MMIO Intel CPUs vulnerabilities related to execution in virtual environments were announced.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] In July 2022, the **Retbleed** vulnerability was disclosed affecting Intel Core 6 to 8th generation CPUs and AMD Zen 1, 1+ and 2 generation CPUs.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] Newer Intel microarchitectures as well as AMD starting with Zen 3 are not affected.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] The mitigations for the vulnerability decrease the performance of the affected Intel CPUs by up to 39%, while AMD CPUs lose up to 14%.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] In August 2022, the **SQUIP** vulnerability was disclosed affecting Ryzen 2000–5000 series CPUs.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] According to AMD the existing mitigations are enough to protect from it.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] According to a Phoronix review released in October, 2022 Zen 4/Ryzen 7000 CPUs are not slowed down by mitigations, in fact disabling them leads to a performance loss.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] In February 2023 a vulnerability affecting a wide range of AMD CPU architectures called "**Cross-Thread Return Address Predictions**" was disclosed.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] In July 2023 a critical vulnerability in the Zen 2 AMD microarchitecture called **Zenbleed** was made public.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] AMD released a microcode update to fix it.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] In August 2023 a vulnerability in AMD's Zen 1, Zen 2, Zen 3, and Zen 4 microarchitectures called **Inception** was revealed and assigned CVE-2023-20569.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] According to AMD it is not practical but the company released a microcode update for the affected products.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] Also in August 2023 a new vulnerability called **Downfall** or **Gather Data Sampling** was disclosed, affecting Intel CPU Skylake, Cascade Lake, Cooper Lake, Ice Lake, Tiger Lake, Amber Lake, Kaby Lake, Coffee Lake, Whiskey Lake, Comet Lake & Rocket Lake CPU families.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] Intel will release a microcode update for affected products.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] The **SLAM** vulnerability (**Spectre based on Linear Address Masking**) reported in 2023 neither has received a corresponding CVE, nor has been confirmed or mitigated against.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] In March 2024, a variant of Spectre-V1 attack called **GhostRace** was published.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] It was claimed it affected all the major microarchitectures and vendors, including Intel, AMD and ARM.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] AMD dismissed the vulnerability (calling it "Speculative Race Conditions (SRCs)") claiming that existing mitigations were enough.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] Linux kernel developers chose not to add mitigations citing performance concerns.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] The Xen hypervisor project released patches to mitigate the vulnerability but they are not enabled by default.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] Also in March 2024, a vulnerability in Intel Atom processors called **Register File Data Sampling** (**RFDS**) was revealed.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] Its mitigations incur a slight performance degradation.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] In April 2024, it was revealed that the BHI vulnerability in certain Intel CPU families could be still exploited in Linux entirely in user space without using any kernel features or root access despite existing mitigations.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] Intel recommended "additional software hardening".
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] In June 2024, Samsung Research and Seoul National University researchers revealed the **TikTag** attack against the Memory Tagging Extension in ARM v8.5A CPUs.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] The researchers created PoCs for Google Chrome and the Linux kernel.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] Researchers from VUSec previously revealed ARM's Memory Tagging Extension is vulnerable to speculative probing.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] In July 2024, UC San Diego researchers revealed the **Indirector** attack against Intel Alder Lake and Raptor Lake CPUs leveraging high-precision Branch Target Injection (BTI).
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] Intel downplayed the severity of the vulnerability and claimed the existing mitigations are enough to tackle the issue.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] In January 2025, Georgia Institute of Technology researchers published two whitepapers on **Data Speculation Attacks via Load Address Prediction on Apple Silicon (SLAP)** and Breaking the Apple M3 CPU via False Load Output Predictions (FLOP).
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] Also in January 2025, ARM disclosed a vulnerability (CVE-2024-7881) in which an unprivileged context can trigger a data memory-dependent prefetch engine to fetch data from a privileged location, potentially leading to unauthorized access.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] To mitigate the issue, Arm recommends disabling the affected prefetcher by setting CPUACTLR6_EL1[41].
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] In May 2025, VUSec released three vulnerabilities extending on Spectre-v2 in various Intel and ARM architectures under the moniker **Training Solo**.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] Mitigations require a microcode update for Intel CPUs and changes in the Linux kernel.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] Also in May 2025, ETH Zurich Computer Security Group "COMSEC" disclosed the **Branch Privilege Injection** vulnerability affecting all Intel x86 architectures starting from the 9th generation (Coffee Lake Refresh) under CVE-2024-45332.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] A microcode update is required to mitigate it.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] It comes with a performance cost up to 8%.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] In July 2025, AMD disclosed a new class of speculative execution vulnerabilities known as **Transient Scheduler Attacks (TSA)**, which were discovered by researchers from Microsoft.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] The attacks are affecting AMD Zen 3 and Zen 4 microarchitectures, and they exploit microarchitectural timing leaks in CPU scheduler logic—specifically, the forwarding of incorrect data during false completion of speculative loads—to infer sensitive data from other processes or privilege levels.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] TSA encompasses four vulnerabilities: CVE-2024-36350 (TSA-SQ), which leaks data from prior stores; CVE-2024-36357 (TSA-L1), which leverages the L1 data cache; CVE-2024-36348, enabling speculative reads of control registers; and CVE-2024-36349, which leaks TSC_AUX register values.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] Mitigations include microcode updates, Linux kernel patches (`tsa=` tunable), and optional use of the `VERW` instruction—albeit with potential performance costs.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] The flaw affects AMD Zen 1–5 and Intel “Coffee Lake” processors, and mitigations include Linux kernel patches that conditionally issue Indirect Branch Prediction Barrier (IBPB) instructions on VMEXITs before returning control to user-space in order to flush predictor state.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] The researchers demonstrated that even relatively "simple" in-order RISC-V cores can leak sensitive information through timing channels, unprivileged performance counters, and undocumented vendor-specific extensions.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] The authors argued that manual analysis of such designs does not scale and presented **RISCover**, an open-source differential fuzzing framework, to compare architectural behavior across cores and configurations.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] In April 2026, Floating Point Divider State Sampling (FP-DSS), a transient execution vulnerability, affecting multiple generations of AMD CPUs, was reported in a paper titled "TREVEX: A Black-Box Detection Framework For Data-Flow Transient Execution Vulnerabilities".
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] Spectre class vulnerabilities will remain unfixed because otherwise CPU designers will have to disable speculative execution which will entail a massive performance loss.
[src:spectre-mitigation/speculative-execution-cpu-vulnerabilities] Despite this, AMD has managed to design Zen 4 such a way its performance is *not* affected by mitigations.
